\section{Model description and some preliminaries}\label{preliminaries}
We consider a complex dynamical network consisting of $N$ linearly
coupled identical nodes. Each node is an $n$-dimensional system
composed of linear term and nonlinear term. The $i$-th node can be
described by following differential equation:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{model-0}
\dot{x}_{i}(t)=Cx_{i}(t)+Bf(x_{i}(t)),
\end{eqnarray}
where $x_{i}(t)=[x_{i1}(t),x_{i2}(t),...,x_{in}(t)]^T$ is the state
vector of the $i$-th node at time $t$; $C\in \mathbb{R}^{n\times
n}$, $B\in \mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$; and
$f(x_{i}(t))=[f_{1}(x_{i1}(t)),f_{2}(x_{i2}(t)),...,
f_{n}(x_{in}(t))]^T$.

The dynamical behavior of the complex dynamical network can be
described by the following linearly coupled differential equations
(\cite{wangxf2002ieeetcas54,wucw2007book})
\begin{eqnarray}\label{model-1}
\hspace{-1cm}\dot{x}_{i}(t)=Cx_{i}(t)+Bf(x_{i}(t))+c\sum\limits_{j=1,j\neq
i}^N a_{ij}\Gamma (x_{j}(t)-x_i(t)),\nonumber\\i=1,...,N,~
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Gamma$ is the inner coupling positive definite matrix
between two connected nodes $i$ and $j$; $c$ is the coupling
strength; and $a_{ij}$ is defined as follows: if there is a
connection from node $j$ to node $i$ ($j\neq i$), then $a_{ij}> 0$;
otherwise, $a_{ij}=0$.

In the process of signal transmission, the coupled states
$x_{j}(t)-x_i(t)$ between connected nodes $j$ and $i$ are suddenly
changed in the form of impulses at discrete times $t_k$. That is,
$x_i(t_k^+)-x_j(t_k^+)=S_k \cdot (x_i(t_k^-)-x_j(t_k^-))$. For the
sake of analytical simplification, we shall choose constant impulse
gain in the form of $S_k=\mu I$, which does not cause any loss of
generality in the sense of synchronization analysis. Let
$a_{ii}=-\sum_{j=1,j\neq i}^N a_{ij}$. Thus, the impulsive dynamical
network can be obtained in the following form:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{model-2}
\left\{\begin{array}{rcl} \dot{x}_{i}(t)=Cx_{i}(t)+Bf(x_{i}(t))
+c\sum\limits_{j=1}^N a_{ij}\Gamma x_{j}(t),\\
t\geq 0,~t\neq t_k,~k\in \mathbb{N},\\
x_j(t_k^+)-x_i(t_k^+)=\mu \cdot
(x_j(t_k^-)-x_i(t_k^-)),\hspace{0.6cm}\\~\mbox{for}~
(i,j)~\mbox{satisfying}~a_{ij}>0, \mu \neq 0,
\end{array}\right.
\end{eqnarray}
where $\zeta=\{t_1,t_2,t_3,...\}$ is an impulsive sequence
satisfying $t_{k-1}<t_k$ and $\lim t_k\rightarrow +\infty$ as
$k\rightarrow +\infty$, and $\mu$ represents the strength of
impulsive signal. Here, $A=(a_{ij})_{N\times N}$ is the Laplacian
matrix of the corresponding network (\cite{chung1997book}). We
always assume that $x_i(t)$ is left-hand continuous at $t=t_k$,
i.e., $x(t_k)=x(t_k^-)$. Hence, the solutions of (\ref{model-2}) are
piecewise left-hand continuous functions with discontinuities at
$t=t_k$ for $k\in \mathbb{N}$.

\begin{remark}
If $u=0$, then the dynamical network \eqref{model-2} would be
synchronized after one impulse. Hence, this trivial case will not be
discussed in the rest of this paper.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}
From the second equation of \eqref{model-2}, we can derive that
$x_i(t_k^+)=\mu \cdot
x_i(t_k^-)+\tilde{c}_k(\forall~\tilde{c}_k\in\mathbb{R}^n)$, which
further implies that $x_i(t_k^+)-c_k=\mu \cdot(
x_i(t_k^-)-c_k)(\forall~c_k\in\mathbb{R}^n)$. Then, the impulses
occurred in the process of coupling can be essentially regarded that
same impulsive controllers are operated on the nodes of the network.
Hence, corresponding impulsive control strategy can be developed to
decide the value of $x_i(t_k^+)$.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Discussions about impulsive sequences}
Here we give some mathematical definitions for three kinds of
impulses, which are respectively desynchronizing impulses, inactive
impulses and synchronizing impulses, in terms of impulsive strength
$\mu$.

\begin{itemize}
\item When $|\mu|>1$, the impulses can potentially destroy the
synchronization since the differences between the nodes' states are
enlarged. Thus we say that the impulses are \textit{desynchronizing}
if $|\mu|>1$. Desynchronizing impulses can be regarded as
perturbations, which can suppress the synchronization of CDNs.

\item When $|\mu|=1$, the impulses are neither harmful nor beneficial for the
synchronization of impulsive dynamical networks since the absolute
value of the differences between the nodes' states remains
unchanged. Hence, the impulses with $|\mu|=1$ are named as
\textit{inactive impulses}.

\item When $|\mu|<1$, the impulses are beneficial for the
synchronization of impulsive dynamical networks since the
differences between the nodes' states are reduced. Thus we say that
the impulses are \textit{synchronizing} if $|\mu|<1$. Synchronizing
impulses can be considered as impulsive controllers, which can
enhance the synchronization of CDNs.
\end{itemize}

When the network dynamics are synchronizing but the impulsive
effects are desynchronizing, the impulses should not occur too
frequently in order to guarantee synchronization. To ensure that the
impulses do not occur too frequently, there always exist a
requirement that $t_{k}-t_{k-1}\geq\varepsilon_1$ for certain
positive number $\varepsilon_1$ in most of the previous results
(\cite{yangz2005ieeetcasii517,zhouj2007phya684}). It means that the
quantity $\varepsilon_1$ is taken as a measure to ensure that the
desynchronizing impulses do not occur too frequently.

Conversely, when the network dynamic are desynchronizing and the
impulsive effects are synchronizing, in order to ensure
synchronization, it should be naturally assumed that the frequency
of impulses should not be too low. To satisfy such assumption, in
most of the previous papers
(\cite{zhangqj2009cma1073,zhangh2006cdc2765,liub2008na1169,liub2005ieeetcasi1431,zhangg2007chaos043126,caism2008pla4990}),
there always exist a requirement that
$t_{k}-t_{k-1}\leq\varepsilon_2$ for certain positive number
$\varepsilon_2$. This means that the quantity $\varepsilon_2$ is
selected as a measure to guarantee that there is no overly long
impulsive intervals.

\subsection{Some preliminaries}
\begin{definition}\label{definition-average-impulsive-interval}
\textit{(average impulsive interval)} The \textit{average impulsive
interval} of the impulsive sequence $\zeta=\{t_1,t_2,\cdots\}$ is
equal to $T_a$ if there exist positive integer $N_0$ and positive
number $T_a$, such that
\begin{eqnarray}\label{model-3}
\hspace{-0.3cm}\frac{T-t}{T_a}-N_0\leq N_{\zeta}(T,t)\leq
\frac{T-t}{T_a}+N_0,~\forall T\geq t\geq 0,~
\end{eqnarray}
where $N_{\zeta}(T,t)$ denotes the number of impulsive times of the
impulsive sequence $\zeta$ on the interval ($t,T$).
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
\textbf{The motivation for the introduction of this concept:} For
most of the real-world impulsive signals, the occurrence of impulses
is not uniformly distributed. Figure \ref{fig:0} presents a specific
example of non-uniformly distributed impulsive sequence. We can
observe from Figure \ref{fig:0} that the impulses seldom occur in
the time intervals $(t^1,t^2)$, whereas they frequently occur in the
interval $(t^2,t^3)$. For such impulsive signals, the lower bound of
the impulsive intervals is small, meanwhile the upper bound of the
impulsive intervals is quite large. Hence, for non-uniformly
distributed impulsive signals, taking $\inf_{k\in
\mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}$ (lower bound) or $\sup_{k\in
\mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}$ (upper bound) to characterize the
frequency of impulses' occurrence would make the obtained results
very conservative. Some previous results in the literature can not
be effectively applied to dynamical systems with the impulsive
signal shown in Figure \ref{fig:0}. For more detailed discussions
about this kind of impulsive signal, please refer to Example
\ref{example:0} in Appendix.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}
It follows from Definition
\ref{definition-average-impulsive-interval} that the average
impulsive interval of impulsive signal $\bar{\zeta}$ in
\eqref{equation-00} is equal to $T_a$. Suppose that $\zeta$ is an
impulsive signal with average impulsive interval $T_a$. It can be
concluded that, for such $\zeta$, the lower bound of the impulsive
intervals can be arbitrarily small; and meanwhile the upper bound of
the impulsive intervals can be very large. Hence, this concept of
\textit{average impulsive interval} is suitable for a wider range of
impulsive signals.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}
The concept of ``\textit{average impulsive interval}" is introduced
by referring to the concept of average dwell time
(\cite{hespanha1999cdc2655,liberzon2003book,hespanha2005cdc3992}) to
characterize how often or how seldom impulses occur. This new
concept will be utilized to derive a \textit{unified} criterion for
the synchronization analysis of impulsive dynamical networks, which
is simultaneously applicable for CDNs with desynchronizing impulses
or synchronizing impulses. The derived criterion is valid for the
impulsive signal in Figure \ref{fig:0}, and further it is applicable
to impulsive signals with a wider range of impulsive interval.
%According to theoretical analysis and numerical examples, the
%obtained criterion is less conservative than previous results.
\end{remark}

