\begin{example}\rm\label{example:2}
We consider an NW directed small-world network
(\cite{newman1999pre7332}) with \textit{synchronizing impulses} as
the second example. In this example, the parameters are set as
$N=200$, $k=2$, and edge-adding probability $0.01$. Thus, a
small-world network can be generated. For this generated small-world
network, the quantities are respectively
$\lambda_{\mbox{max}}(W)=0.00817$ and
$\lambda_2(\tilde{A})=-0.0129$. Hence, one can obtain that
$\gamma=-\lambda_2(\tilde{A})/\lambda_{\max}(W)=1.58$. Let $c=5$ and
$\Gamma=I_3$. By simple computation, we can obtain that $p=3.6752$.

Let the strength of the synchronizing impulsive be $\mu=0.8$ and
average impulsive interval be $T_a=0.12$. Hence, we can obtain that
$\eta=-0.04385$. According to Theorem \ref{theorem-1}, it can be
concluded that a complex dynamical network with synchronizing
impulses can be synchronized. Figure \ref{fig:3} represents an
impulsive sequence with $N_0=10$ and $T_a=0.12$, and error
trajectories of the small-world coupled dynamical network are
plotted in Figure \ref{fig:4}.

For the impulsive signal in Figure \ref{fig:3}, the upper bound of
the impulsive intervals is 0.93. If we utilize $\sup_{k\in
\mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}=0.93$ instead of $T_a$, $\eta_{\sup}$
becomes 3.19532 and criterion \eqref{equation-02} is not satisfied.
Hence, for this example, criterion \eqref{equation-02} can not be
utilized to judge whether the impulsive dynamical network can be
synchronized if $\sup_{k\in \mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}$ is used.
Hence, our analytical result \eqref{equation-0} is less conservative
than the results in
\cite{zhangqj2009cma1073,zhangh2006cdc2765,liub2008na1169,liub2005ieeetcasi1431,zhangg2007chaos043126,caism2008pla4990}.
\end{example}

