\section*{Appendix}
\begin{example}\label{example:0}
This example is devoted to the discussion of non-uniformly
distributed impulses. A specific example is given to show that lower
bound or upper bound of impulsive intervals, which has been widely
used in literature, can not precisely describe the occurrence
frequency of impulses.

We give a specific impulsive signal as
$\bar{\zeta}=\{\epsilon,2\epsilon,...,(N_0-1)\epsilon,N_0T_a,N_0T_a+\epsilon,N_0T_a+2\epsilon,...,N_0T_a+(N_0-1)\epsilon,2N_0T_a,...\}$,
where $\epsilon$ and $T_a$ are positive numbers satisfies
$\epsilon<T_a$, and $N_0$ is a positive integer. The impulsive
signal $\bar{\zeta}=\{t_1,t_2,t_3,...\}$ can also be re-written in
the following form:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{equation-00}
\hspace{-0.5cm}t_k-t_{k-1}=\left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\epsilon,&\hspace{0.1cm}\mbox{if}~\mbox{mod}(k,N_0)\neq0,\\
N_0(T_a-\epsilon)+\epsilon,&\hspace{0.1cm}\mbox{if}~\mbox{mod}(k,N_0)=0.~
\end{array}\right.
\end{eqnarray}

\begin{figure}[!htbp]\centering
\includegraphics[width=8cm,height=5.2cm]{sec2.3_typical_impulsive_sequence.eps}
\caption{Example of a specific impulsive sequence described in
\eqref{equation-00} with $\epsilon=0.05$, $N_0=10$ and $T_a=0.5$.
Such an impulsive sequence simultaneously owns small lower bound and
large upper bound of impulsive intervals.} \label{fig:0}
\end{figure}

From the structure of the impulsive signal $\bar{\zeta}$, we can
obtain that $\inf_{k\in \mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}=\epsilon$ and
$\sup_{k\in
\mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}=N_0(T_a-\epsilon)+\epsilon$. Figure
\ref{fig:0} represents such an impulsive signal with
$\epsilon=0.05$, $N_0=10$ and $T_a=0.5$. It can be observed from
Figure \ref{fig:0} that impulses occur frequently in $(t^2,t^3)$,
whereas they seldom occur in $(t^1,t^2)$. When $\epsilon$ is
sufficiently small and $N_0$ is sufficiently large, the quantity
$\inf_{k\in \mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}=\epsilon$ will be very
small, and the quantity $\sup_{k\in
\mathbb{N}^+}\{t_{k}-t_{k-1}\}=N_0(T_a-\epsilon)+\epsilon$ will be
very big. Under such circumstance, the results in
(\cite{zhouj2007phya684,yangz2005ieeetcasii517,zhangqj2009cma1073,zhangh2006cdc2765,liub2008na1169,liub2005ieeetcasi1431,zhangg2007chaos043126,caism2008pla4990}),
would not be applicable.
\end{example}

